00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:59.040
But one that came in from Gustavo was, would you include the educational level as a factor

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:03.239
after looking at those accuracy results from the model?

00:07:03.239 --> 00:07:06.600
Really out of scope for this demo, but that might be a question raised by someone going

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:08.000
through the model card.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:09.000
Yeah.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.359
So this is, this is a question about the process of developing the model.

00:07:12.359 --> 00:07:15.799
And I think it's a really interesting one to at least briefly talk about.

00:07:15.799 --> 00:07:20.859
So the, it was not one of the predictors.

00:07:20.859 --> 00:07:25.640
So educational level, like, like is someone, how much education did one of these employees

00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:32.160
have was not one of the predictors to predict their, you know, whether like attrition, like

00:07:32.160 --> 00:07:33.720
whether they were going to leave or not.

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:42.320
But then after analyzing the model, you're like, oh, we do a better job predicting attrition

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:46.519
for the high levels of education and a worse job for the low level ones.

00:07:46.519 --> 00:07:53.279
So it turns out in situations like this, if you try to put that characteristic into the

00:07:53.279 --> 00:07:56.640
model, it often doesn't help you predict any better.

00:07:56.640 --> 00:08:01.200
Like, like you still, it does not improve your ability to predict attrition for the

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:04.040
lower level education people.

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:09.880
Usually you, the, you know, like why, why does this, why does it happen that like some,

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:14.040
some characteristics, it's people with certain care, like demographic characteristics, like

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:16.079
the model performs work for them.

00:08:16.079 --> 00:08:22.200
Usually it is because there's like the, the most common thing is there's less data for

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:23.200
those people.

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:28.160
So putting that as a factor, like as a predictor in the model doesn't actually help you.

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:32.599
And it may actually make the water perform worse overall for everyone.

00:08:32.599 --> 00:08:41.159
The thing that you might want to do is to try different kinds of models and to see which

00:08:41.159 --> 00:08:49.840
one does the most, let's say even job across the characteristics.

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:53.760
And that's exactly where fairness metrics come in.

00:08:53.760 --> 00:09:00.880
So Rachel, I am going to drop you a link for someone who wants to learn more about this.

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:05.919
If you are in the process of developing a model and you notice that you have this kind

00:09:05.919 --> 00:09:13.400
of differential across categories and you want to say, can I minimize that differential

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:21.359
so that my model performs fairly across different characteristics, there's support for comparing

00:09:21.359 --> 00:09:23.919
models with fairness metrics.

00:09:23.919 --> 00:09:25.640
And that's exactly what that gets you.

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:31.799
But often, often it, it does not help the situation at all to put the demographic characteristic

00:09:31.799 --> 00:09:32.799
as a predictor.

00:09:32.799 --> 00:09:37.320
Like it does, it doesn't even like, it doesn't, it's very common for it not to help.

00:09:37.320 --> 00:09:39.760
Like that's not a solution to the problem typically.

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:40.799
So great question.

00:09:40.799 --> 00:09:41.799
Really great question.

00:09:42.200 --> 00:09:43.200
Thank you.

