00:09:59.200 --> 00:10:01.599
Let's see.

00:10:01.599 --> 00:10:06.320
There is a question that was, would love to hear any thoughts or discourse on publishing

00:10:06.320 --> 00:10:08.080
dates on the model card.

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:12.840
Would it be possible to parametrize the date to capture data changes?

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:13.840
Yeah.

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:23.159
So you may notice that, so a model card is a human evaluation, human documentation about

00:10:23.159 --> 00:10:28.880
like what is, like how is the model performing at a certain time?

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:32.080
It's about the model that you trained.

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:35.280
It's less about the model's performance over time.

00:10:35.799 --> 00:10:41.239
Although of course, like we talked about with the dashboard, like you can kind of get those,

00:10:41.239 --> 00:10:45.880
you can present those in a combined way with a fair amount of clarity.

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:54.039
I think that I typically 100% parametrize the date so that it is clear that when people

00:10:54.039 --> 00:10:59.119
look at it, they know how old, you know, like when was the last time this model was looked

00:10:59.119 --> 00:11:00.119
at?

00:11:00.119 --> 00:11:04.159
If you'll notice in the Quarto file, like you can click through to the GitHub repo and

00:11:04.159 --> 00:11:13.599
see like I, in the Quarto file I used for a model card, it said like last edited or

00:11:13.599 --> 00:11:15.880
let me get exactly what it was called.

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:19.159
It's like the date is defined as last modified.

00:11:19.159 --> 00:11:24.559
And so that means that when that is published, I don't have to manually think about that

00:11:24.559 --> 00:11:25.559
at all actually.

00:11:25.559 --> 00:11:29.640
Like I get that information automatically there.

00:11:29.640 --> 00:11:34.400
The other thing that I think that is really nice along these lines is in that model details

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:44.000
section, we say not only, we automatically read off not only the version from the metadata,

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:48.179
but also the date that the model was published.

00:11:48.179 --> 00:11:51.359
So we get all that quite automatically.

00:11:51.359 --> 00:11:54.880
And I think it's interesting because like this isn't like when it comes to documenting

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:57.799
models, some things can be automated, right?

00:11:57.799 --> 00:11:59.400
Like we can get that information.

00:12:00.159 --> 00:12:01.159
Let's automate that.

00:12:01.159 --> 00:12:02.359
Let's make that easier.

00:12:02.359 --> 00:12:07.320
But some things do require that like human evaluation, human thought, human writing.

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:13.640
And we can make that, like set ourselves up for success for that, but be realistic that

00:12:13.640 --> 00:12:15.640
it can't be automated.

00:12:15.640 --> 00:12:17.640
Thank you.

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:18.640
Okay.

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:24.440
Let me do one more Slido and then we'll jump over to some of the YouTube ones.

00:12:24.440 --> 00:12:28.280
This question was, who contributes to writing a model card?

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:31.359
Roles of the data scientists, stakeholders, privacy team?

00:12:31.359 --> 00:12:32.359
Yes.

00:12:32.359 --> 00:12:37.080
Oh, I love this question.

00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:44.039
I observe that the most common person to write the model card is the person who developed

00:12:44.039 --> 00:12:45.039
the model.

00:12:45.039 --> 00:12:50.320
And I think that's the healthiest, I think that it turns out that way because that's

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:54.039
the person who has the most context for it.

00:12:54.640 --> 00:13:01.119
Like the person who developed the model itself has, you know, knows what went into the process

00:13:01.119 --> 00:13:08.200
of deciding on one type of model versus another, who's done the exploratory data analysis on

00:13:08.200 --> 00:13:18.919
the data available at training time, and then is able to, you know, make substantive, realistic

00:13:18.919 --> 00:13:24.359
claims about the training data, about the data that has been used to evaluate the model.

00:13:24.359 --> 00:13:28.119
Like I think that's the person who has the most responsibility here.

00:13:28.119 --> 00:13:35.719
The data, the model card, the primary responsibility lies with the person who developed, the person

00:13:35.719 --> 00:13:37.960
or team who developed the model.

00:13:37.960 --> 00:13:44.159
I do think that like you're writing for an audience of someone, right?

00:13:44.159 --> 00:13:49.000
Like someone who, some stakeholder who is going to use the model to do something, whether

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:53.440
that is a software engineer, collaborator who needs to know how to integrate the model

00:13:53.440 --> 00:14:00.479
into an IT system, or someone who's making decisions based on the, like maybe a business

00:14:00.479 --> 00:14:01.479
stakeholder.

00:14:01.479 --> 00:14:12.239
So, I think that as those stakeholders probably are not writing the model card, but they are

00:14:12.239 --> 00:14:17.239
the ones who, like the model card needs to be useful to them.

00:14:17.239 --> 00:14:23.840
And so, contributing to like what needs to be in that model card, I think is really valuable

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:27.479
to bring those stakeholders in.

00:14:27.479 --> 00:14:32.239
I think Justin's question actually ties in really well here as well.

00:14:32.239 --> 00:14:38.400
So, how would you manage those like task assignments, track progress, and assure smooth collaboration

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:41.440
among the team members throughout the process?

00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:48.520
And even like what you just said about making sure that the stakeholders can provide feedback

00:14:48.520 --> 00:14:49.880
on that model card too.

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:50.880
Yeah, yeah.

00:14:50.880 --> 00:15:03.000
So, I think this, I love this question because often these kinds of zones of responsibility

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:10.000
or zones of influence often are at the boundaries of the kinds of tools people use.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:14.760
For example, the person who is writing the model card, who developed the model and is

00:15:14.760 --> 00:15:21.679
writing the model card, often is using like code-based tools, code-first tools, right?

00:15:21.679 --> 00:15:29.359
And so, they're like, if you're, and you end up with, I think one of the real challenges,

00:15:29.359 --> 00:15:35.400
one of the real like tensions in doing data work where your stakeholders are not people

00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:40.000
who are hands-on with the data, not people who are writing code themselves.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.039
How do you elicit feedback?

00:15:43.039 --> 00:15:44.640
How do you integrate feedback?

00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:48.280
This is for sure not a solved problem at all.

00:15:48.280 --> 00:15:53.440
The things that I have used, this is, my answer right here is about to be super practical.

00:15:53.440 --> 00:15:59.520
The things I've done in the past that have, I have found useful, like sometimes I will

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:07.119
publish, I have published things to connect, deposit connect, and then, you know, shared

00:16:07.119 --> 00:16:09.080
and gotten feedback on that way.

00:16:09.080 --> 00:16:16.200
The other thing I have done in the past is I have published drafts of things to something

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:27.400
more, something more like Google Drive, Google Docs, the Microsoft equivalents, so that,

00:16:27.400 --> 00:16:34.359
and then like literally ask people for feedback on an initial draft before publishing a final

00:16:34.359 --> 00:16:35.359
version.

00:16:35.359 --> 00:16:39.840
This, I think this is, there is some real tension, there is some real tension at this

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:45.200
intersection of people who are hands-on with the data and how to get feedback from people

00:16:45.200 --> 00:16:48.000
who are the stakeholders in the results there.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.000
Thank you.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:57.440
So, Brendan had asked a question earlier during the demo, and it was, are there plans to extend

00:16:57.440 --> 00:17:01.200
model cards to be able to evaluate third-party models?

00:17:01.200 --> 00:17:03.599
Well, we can all read it here.

00:17:03.599 --> 00:17:05.560
I guess I'll read the rest as well.

00:17:05.560 --> 00:17:11.160
One framework to evaluate homegrown and third-party models could help the build versus buy decision

00:17:11.160 --> 00:17:12.760
that plagues many orgs.

00:17:12.760 --> 00:17:13.760
Yeah.

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:20.920
So, if you are, so, it depends, so, like, let's, I'm going to make some assumptions

00:17:20.920 --> 00:17:23.479
about what we mean here by third-party models.

00:17:23.479 --> 00:17:30.040
So, for example, someone else has trained a model, and you are going to use the model

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:33.479
kind of as a black box, like you're going to send your data in and you're going to get

00:17:33.479 --> 00:17:34.479
a prediction out.

00:17:34.479 --> 00:17:40.000
You know, these kinds of models, they could be predictive models, right, like there are

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.319
like models as a service, right?

00:17:42.319 --> 00:17:48.040
And then there's the sort of the more, you know, generative AI type models, right, like

00:17:48.040 --> 00:17:53.400
that it's very common to be in a build versus buy situation where you're like, we are not

00:17:53.400 --> 00:17:55.599
going to train that ourselves, right?

00:17:55.599 --> 00:18:03.199
I am going to say that, like, the person who is responsible for the model card is the person

00:18:03.199 --> 00:18:10.400
who knows about the training data, is the person who knows what went into, what went

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:15.280
into getting that model to the point that it can make predictions.

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:20.439
And you as a customer who doesn't have that transparency, like, I don't even know how

00:18:20.439 --> 00:18:24.079
you would write a model card, like, because you don't have that information.

