So, the short answer is no.

00:22:22.280 --> 00:22:23.640
They are quite different.

00:22:23.640 --> 00:22:25.640
They are quite different in some real ways.

00:22:27.239 --> 00:22:36.599
RStudio is, like, we at Posit are committed to, you know, new features, bug fixes, maintenance

00:22:36.599 --> 00:22:39.560
for RStudio for a very long time, right?

00:22:40.359 --> 00:22:44.520
RStudio has been around for, like, 10, 15 years.

00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:51.800
And there is not a world or future in which, like, we are not doing, like, maintenance for

00:22:51.800 --> 00:22:56.359
RStudio, like, within the scope of any kind of plans that we are making.

00:22:56.920 --> 00:23:03.959
And, in fact, RStudio may likely be a better choice of an IDE for many of you today and,

00:23:03.959 --> 00:23:06.599
you know, for a little while in the future.

00:23:06.599 --> 00:23:18.439
That's because RStudio is, if you only write R, if you only write R, like, RStudio is likely

00:23:20.199 --> 00:23:23.000
like a very good, perhaps best choice for you, actually.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:26.760
Because RStudio is built specifically for an R user.

00:23:27.479 --> 00:23:33.079
I would say if you're interested in Positron, I think there are three kinds of, like, if you

00:23:33.079 --> 00:23:34.920
want to say, like, hey, is Positron for me?

00:23:34.920 --> 00:23:36.439
Should I try out Positron?

00:23:36.439 --> 00:23:41.479
And I think there's a couple of answers that would, if you are an RStudio user, I think

00:23:41.479 --> 00:23:45.719
there are a couple of things that might say, like, yeah, maybe I should give Positron a try.

00:23:45.719 --> 00:23:52.359
One is you are, like, a maximizer when it comes to customization.

00:23:52.359 --> 00:23:57.319
Like, you love to, like, majorly bling out your IDE and customize it.

00:23:57.319 --> 00:24:01.640
And you love setting up keyboard shortcuts and, like, really customizing.

00:24:01.640 --> 00:24:03.000
You're kind of a power user.

00:24:04.760 --> 00:24:10.280
Positron, because of the infrastructure it's built on, has a much higher ability for you

00:24:10.280 --> 00:24:17.560
to customize and exactly make it exactly how you want than RStudio ever has and ever will

00:24:17.560 --> 00:24:19.160
because of the architecture that's built on.

00:24:19.160 --> 00:24:24.920
So, number one, you are a power user maximizer type person.

00:24:24.920 --> 00:24:27.640
Number two, you don't only use R.

00:24:28.520 --> 00:24:36.280
You maybe build R packages that include Rust code or you build really complex shiny apps

00:24:36.280 --> 00:24:42.119
that use a lot of JavaScript and, like, you're writing custom JavaScript that you integrate

00:24:42.119 --> 00:24:43.160
into a shiny app.

00:24:43.959 --> 00:24:49.800
Or, you know, you use R and Python for, you know, for your data science projects.

00:24:49.800 --> 00:24:56.599
If you are not an only R user, then Positron is a really great fit for you.

00:24:56.599 --> 00:25:00.920
So, these are, like, these are the kinds of things that I would say in the short to

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:08.040
medium term would be reasons to try Positron versus if you're a happy, so, if you are a

00:25:08.040 --> 00:25:14.359
happy RStudio user, do feel no, you should feel no pressure to change and you should

00:25:14.359 --> 00:25:17.000
feel no stress that your IDE is going away.

